<item>
            <title>[LUCENE-285] David Spencer Spell Checker improved</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/LUCENE-285</link>
                <project id="12310110" key="LUCENE">Lucene - Core</project>
                        <description>&lt;p&gt;hy,&lt;br/&gt;
i developed a SpellChecker based on the David Spencer code (DSc) but more flexible.&lt;br/&gt;
the structure of the index is inspired of the DSc (for a 3-4 gram):&lt;br/&gt;
word:&lt;br/&gt;
gram3:&lt;br/&gt;
gram4:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3start:&lt;br/&gt;
4start:&lt;br/&gt;
..&lt;br/&gt;
3end:&lt;br/&gt;
4end:&lt;br/&gt;
..&lt;br/&gt;
transposition:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This index is a dictonary so there isn&apos;t the &quot;freq&quot; field like with DSc version.&lt;br/&gt;
it&apos;s independant of the user index. So we can add words becoming to several&lt;br/&gt;
fields of several index for example or, why not, to a file with a list of words.&lt;br/&gt;
The suggestSimilar method return a list of suggests word sorted by the&lt;br/&gt;
Levenshtein distance and optionaly to the popularity of the word for a specific&lt;br/&gt;
field in a user index. More of that, this list can be restricted only to words&lt;br/&gt;
present in a specific field of a user index.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See the test case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i hope this code will be put in the lucene sandbox. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nicolas Maisonneuve&lt;/p&gt;</description>
